The Project is multi-country across Peru   Bolivia and Ecuador   and it aims to contribute to the enjoyment of food security in poor regions of Bolivia   Peru and Ecuador by creating spaces for dialogue and participation between farmers and local governments.  It will strengthen the ability of farmers organisations to lobby and participate in decision making spaces around food security and nutrition by advocating for the design   implementation and monitoring of public policies and programs at the local regional and national level.

The project is the second phase of the Rural WASH project which is now targeting in total 12 new districts. Plan will be implementing the project in Mutoko district is one of the 12 districts. According to the baseline survey conducted in 2016, the district water and sanitation situation has regressed significantly. An estimated 17.6% people in the district do not have access to safe water and 78.4% are without improved sanitation.  Although efforts to put new water infrastructure through drilling of boreholes was done in the past years, most of the boreholes are not functional with some in poor unhygienic condition. The national baseline survey that was carried out revealed that more than 60% of the boreholes in the 3 provinces were non-functional exposing populations to unsafe drinking water sources. With more than 80% of the population in rural areas using un treated water, the district can be considered to have a high water related disease burden.  The country had serious cholera outbreak (2008/2009) and the majority of the cases (72%) were from rural areas, a red flag indicator of poor WASH service delivery system in rural areas. The impact of lack of access to safe water and improved sanitation has a far reaching impact on the lives of children and their communities.

This is a regional project across 5 countries  in Central America.  It aims to strengthen the regional and national advocacy capacity of CSO networks working on childrens rights at national   regional and international levels so as to have promoted a inclusive democratic culture that ensures effective public policies on children's issues from a rights framework   especially targeting the no violence against children and adolescents in Central America.

The overall objective of the project is to contribute to the efforts of Jordan and Lebanon in respecting art 32 of the Convention of the Rights of the Child. The project operates in Aljoufeh and Alkarameh in the Jordan Valley (Jordan) and Kaa in the Beqaa Valley (Lebanon) . The project has four expected outcomes:
1.	Vulnerable targeted boys and girls have decreased vulnerability to worst forms of child labour in the agricultural sector after receiving age appropriate and gender sensitive child protection, non/in formal education and livelihood opportunities. 
2.	Targeted caregivers are willing and enabled to protect their children from worst forms of child labour after participating in Positive Parenting Programme and/or accessing livelihood alternatives.
3.	Local Development Committees, Child Protection Committees, Schools counsellors and communities are better enabled to prevent and respond to the worst forms of child labour.
4.	The implementation of the National Action Plans against the worst forms of child labour of Jordan and Lebanon are supported to respond to the worst forms of child labour.

The overarching goal of the project is gender equality and the realisation of girls  rights in Cambodia. The project purpose is to increase the number of adolescent girls completing Lower Secondary education by addressing some of the key economicand socialand culturaland and political barriers. The project will directly benefit approximately 3000 adolescent girls from 26 Secondary schools across six Districts in Cambodia.

The overall aim of this project is to improve access to and quality delivery of education and Sexual Reproductive Health via Social Accountability. The purpose is to increase the number of adolescent girls enrolling and completing education as well as girls involved in decision making processes in the community and school management. The project also intends to change the attitudes and behaviour of girlsand parentsand communities and officials in relation to adolescent girls  right to educationand gender and sexual reproductive health .
